      <h2>E-Commerce vs Traditional Retail: Warehouse Impact</h2>

      <h3>Traditional Retail Warehouse Patterns</h3>

      <p><strong>Characteristics:</strong>
      <br>• Large orders (50-100 pallets per delivery)
      <br>• Infrequent deliveries (weekly or monthly)
      <br>• Steady, predictable volume
      <br>• Focus on storage efficiency (holding inventory)</p>

      <p><strong>Forklift Needs:</strong>
      <br>• Standard equipment sufficient
      <br>• Emphasis on lift capacity over speed
      <br>• Lower utilization rates (equipment idle between deliveries)</p>

      <h3>E-Commerce Warehouse Patterns</h3>

      <p><strong>Characteristics:</strong>
      <br>• Small orders (1-5 items per order, not pallets)
      <br>• High frequency (daily or hourly order processing)
      <br>• Volatile volume (peaks during sales events, festivals)
      <br>• Focus on picking speed and accuracy</p>

      <p><strong>Forklift Needs:</strong>
      <br>• More equipment (handling many small movements)
      <br>• Emphasis on speed and maneuverability
      <br>• Specialized equipment (narrow aisle, pallet jacks, order pickers)
      <br>• Higher utilization rates (continuous operation)</p>

      <h2>Malaysia E-Commerce Growth: The Numbers</h2>

      <h3>Market Size and Growth</h3>

      <p><strong>2024 E-Commerce Statistics:</strong>
      <br>• Market value: RM160 billion (23% growth from 2023)
      <br>• Online shoppers: 18 million Malaysians (55% of population)
      <br>• Mobile commerce: 72% of online transactions via smartphones
      <br>• Growth projection: 18-22% annually through 2030</p>

      <h3>Key Growth Categories</h3>

